 the correct value and reaches equilibrium again (if it does at all, otherwise
 it dies).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In slightly more abstract term, our minimal example is made up of a 1-dimensiona
l space for the environment, the internal space consists of only one variable
 measuring the location of the organism on the space, the action is a [-1,
 1] velocity vector controlling the location of the organism in the space,
 a feedback loop that seeks to minimize the distance between organism and
 the zero point in the environment by translating the distance into the
 velocity vector.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that even such a simple mono-dimensional organism-environment coupling
 could be made more complex without altering the basic setup.
 For instance, we could imagine having the food source moving along the
 line, in which case a successful organism would be tracking it.
 Or we could imagine having a variable measuring an internal slowly decaying
 value (perhaps modeling a battery-level) and having the motor operating
 only when the battery is below a certain threshold, or the organism dying
 when the level reaches zero.
 Notice also that the input-output relation may not be linear, nor would
 the sensing have to be so.
 It is well-known fact, for instance, that several biological organisms
 sense their environment on a logarithmic scale (i.e., the intensity of the
 internal sensation increases linearly when the value of the external stimulus
 doubles) and it may be appropriate for a biological setup to model the
 sensing apparatus of the agent accordingly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In short, an Ashby-like cybernetic description is based upon the following
 concepts:
\end_layout

