\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a set of monitoring (feedback) loops, typically including a set of organism
 sensors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a set of operations that would change the parameters of the feedback loops
 themselves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
equilibrium as the overall goal of the system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A system is in equilibrium when its internal variables are at zero.
 The system reaches equilibrium (when possible, otherwise it dies) by acting
 upon the environment, i.e.
 by exploiting the affordances the external environment provides that can
 modify its internal space (and therefore alter the value of its internal
 variable).
 The equilibrium-seeking strategy is randomly determined by randomly switching
 through the set of possible values for its input-output connections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Abstract concepts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even though Ashbian cybernetics had a biological inspiration (the human
 brain being its main inspiration), its operational model was not limited
 to the biological domain from the very beginning as cyberneticians really
 very quickly that its basic concepts were abstract enough to warrant applicatio
n to different domains
