\begin_layout Standard
A traditional definition of sound singles out five general parameters: pitch
 (frequency), intensity (amplitude), duration, timbre, and spatialization.
 In the simplest case, pitch is represented by frequency in HZ, intensity
 by an amplitude in Db, duration in 
\emph on
s, 
\emph default
and spatialization by a set of geometrical coordinates ( (typically spherical
 coordinates centered on the hearer
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

s head), while timbre is by far the most complicated parameter.
 Some authors have suggested a three-dimensional characterization of timbre
 measuring the relative intensity of the basic pitch, the 2nd to 4th harmonic,
 and all the other harmonics, and more complex approaches including time-related
 decay (ADSR or similar).
\begin_inset Foot
