\begin_layout Standard
We can divide the agent model into two broad categories corresponding to
 the direction of the agent-environment interaction:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Sensing.

\emph default
 A sound space based agent will obviously need to be able to sense the sonic
 features of the sound space, most likely on a logarithmic basis, and it
 sensing apparatus must correspond to the variable sonic features of the
 provided environment or a subset thereof.
 For instance, assuming a bi-dimensional sound space representing pitch
 and intensity while keeping fix timbre duration and spatialization, we
 could have agents capable of sensing frequency, amplitude or to both, while
 sensitivity to timbre, location, or duration would not not produce any
 movement in the sound environment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Acting
\emph default
.
 An action is a movement across the space capable of directly or indirectly
 changing the value of the agent
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

s sensed input(s).
 In the minimal Braitenberg type-1 example described above, for instance,
 the action of moving along the line changes the distance from the food
 source which is directly sensed by the agent.
 Similarly, in a mono-dimensional frequency sound space an agent could be
 constantly emitting a sound (a behavior analogous to be positioned on a
 line) and be measuring the distance between the its frequency and the frequency
 emitted by a (possibly shifting) environmental sound source.
 The agent
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

s action would be a change in the frequency of the sound it emits.
 In this possible setup, a successful equilibrium-seeking strategy would
 produce a 
\emph on
glissando
\emph default
 from the initial frequency to the environmental source (or a series of
 partial or total 
\emph on
glissandi
\emph default
, in the case of a dynamic environment)
\end_layout

